    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Even more meaningful :</p>\n\n<pre><code>import static org.mockito.Mockito.never;\nimport static org.mockito.Mockito.verify;\n\n// ...\n\nverify(dependency, never()).someMethod();\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>The documentation of this feature is there <a href=\"https://static.javadoc.io/org.mockito/mockito-core/2.7.21/org/mockito/Mockito.html#4\" rel=\"noreferrer\">§4 \"Verifying exact number of invocations / at least x / never\"</a>, and the <code>never</code> javadoc is <a href=\"https://static.javadoc.io/org.mockito/mockito-core/2.7.21/org/mockito/Mockito.html#never_verification\" rel=\"noreferrer\">here</a>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 3220072,
        "reputation" : 797,
        "user_id" : 2717751,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 75,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ba4070c8de9136b810a7d301af97c758?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "Chadi",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2717751/chadi"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 10,
      "creation_date" : 1457098316,
      "post_id" : 28834881,
      "comment_id" : 59264221,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "The Mockito documentation states that this pattern should not be abused --  &quot;A word of warning: Some users who did a lot of classic, expect-run-verify mocking tend to use verifyNoMoreInteractions() very often, even in every test method. verifyNoMoreInteractions() is not recommended to use in every test method. verifyNoMoreInteractions() is a handy assertion from the interaction testing toolkit. Use it only when it&#39;s relevant. Abusing it leads to overspecified, less maintainable tests.&quot; See <a href=\"http://site.mockito.org/mockito/docs/current/org/mockito/Mockito.html#8\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">here</a>"
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 1980276,
        "reputation" : 8361,
        "user_id" : 1777072,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 60,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7d62871f14ee1adcdc9d087dc72c5881?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "David Lavender",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1777072/david-lavender"
      },
      "reply_to_user" : {
        "account_id" : 3220072,
        "reputation" : 797,
        "user_id" : 2717751,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 75,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ba4070c8de9136b810a7d301af97c758?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "Chadi",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2717751/chadi"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 4,
      "creation_date" : 1464710133,
      "post_id" : 28834881,
      "comment_id" : 62589276,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "&quot;Use it only when it&#39;s relevant&quot;.  I feel that it is always relevant. I don&#39;t see that pattern as abuse: like I said, it finds &quot;things were being called that shouldn&#39;t have been&quot;.  To me, that&#39;s a vital piece of verification: if something is calling a repository that it shouldn&#39;t be using, I want to know about it!  Unless there&#39;s another way to verify that without using <code>verifyNoMoreInteractions</code>?  The other answers here rely on the test writer explicitly remembering to list out these checks: that&#39;s too error prone in my book."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 33699,
        "reputation" : 313,
        "user_id" : 94540,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6e827d4ba5861431c794d9afabb205e1?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
