      },
      "reply_to_user" : {
        "account_id" : 33699,
        "reputation" : 313,
        "user_id" : 94540,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6e827d4ba5861431c794d9afabb205e1?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "tobinibot",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/94540/tobinibot"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 2,
      "creation_date" : 1537565193,
      "post_id" : 28834881,
      "comment_id" : 91845775,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "@tobinibot Because the idea of unit testing is to verify a Contract. Most contracts don&#39;t typically involved how many times some other method is invoked, but rather that passing in known parameters results in a known response. By using no more interactions you&#39;re basically verifying the implementation line by line, which makes refactoring and implementation tedious. Which isn&#39;t the point of unit testing."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 18853938,
        "reputation" : 308,
        "user_id" : 13752392,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/81a6ea758c5d7c3affdcbfd37c3a2bf7?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "aarowman",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/13752392/aarowman"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 1,
      "creation_date" : 1616707617,
      "post_id" : 28834881,
      "comment_id" : 118095353,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "I&#39;ve run into multiple times where we verify something was not called, then later change the implementation to call something else.. and the old test still passes, because the old method is still not called, but we didn&#39;t verify the new method.  The pattern suggested here will help ensure your test stays relevant - if you update code without updating a test, you may have hidden issues and assume your test still covers it.  I agree with @DavidLavender: &quot;The other answers here rely on the test writer explicitly remembering to list out these checks: that&#39;s too error prone in my book.&quot;"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1980276,
